WEBVTT

00:22.860 --> 00:28.700
XIV. Former Inhabitants and Winter-Visitors

00:30.060 --> 00:36.520
I weathered some merry snow-storms and spent some cheerful winter evenings by my fireside,

00:36.940 --> 00:45.460
while the snow whirled wildly without, and even the hooting of the owl was hushed. For

00:45.460 --> 00:50.940
many weeks I met no one in my walks but those who came occasionally to cut wood and sled

00:50.940 --> 00:57.780
it to the village. The elements, however, abetted me in making a path through the deepest

00:57.780 --> 01:03.740
snow in the woods, for when I had once gone through the wind blew the oak leaves into

01:03.740 --> 01:11.700
my tracks, where they lodged, and by absorbing the rays of the sun melted the snow, and so

01:11.700 --> 01:19.880
not only made a bed for my feet, but in the night their dark line was my guide. For human

01:19.880 --> 01:27.760
society I was obliged to conjure up the former occupants of these woods. Within the memory

01:27.780 --> 01:33.960
of many of my townsmen the road near which my house stands resounded with the laugh and

01:33.960 --> 01:39.360
gossip of inhabitants, and the woods which border it were notched and dotted here and

01:39.360 --> 01:45.560
there with their little gardens and dwellings, though it was then much more shut in by the

01:45.560 --> 01:52.460
forest than now. In some places within my own remembrance the pines would scrape both

01:52.460 --> 01:58.420
sides of a chaise at once, and women and children who were compelled to go this way to Lincoln

01:58.420 --> 02:07.380
alone and on foot did it with fear, and often ran a good deal of the distance. Though mainly

02:07.380 --> 02:14.140
but a humble route to neighboring villages, or for the woodsman's team, it once amused

02:14.140 --> 02:21.740
the traveler more than now by its variety, and lingered longer in his memory. Where now

02:21.740 --> 02:28.760
firm open fields stretched from the village to the woods, it then ran through a maple

02:28.760 --> 02:35.120
swamp on a foundation of logs, the remnants of which doubtless still underlie the present

02:35.120 --> 02:44.660
dusty highway, from the Stratton, now the Alm's House Farm, to Brister's Hill. East

02:44.660 --> 02:52.500
of my bean field, across the road, lived Cato Ingraham, slave of Duncan Ingraham, esquire

02:52.500 --> 02:58.300
gentleman of Concord Village, who built his slave a house, and gave him permission to

02:58.300 --> 03:13.460
live in Walden Woods. Cato, but not Utesensis, but Concordiensis. Some say that he was a

03:13.460 --> 03:18.920
little patch among the walnuts, which he let grow up till he should be old and need them,

03:19.780 --> 03:28.020
but a younger and whiter speculator got them at last. He, too, however, occupies an equally

03:28.020 --> 03:36.500
narrow house at present. Cato's half-obliterated cellar hole still remains, though known to

03:36.500 --> 03:42.760
few, being concealed from the traveler by a fringe of pines. It is now filled with the

03:42.760 --> 03:52.320
smooth sumac rus glabra, and one of the earliest species of golden-rod, Soledago strikta, grows

03:52.320 --> 04:00.320
there luxuriantly. Here, by the very corner of my field still nearer to town, Zilpha,

04:00.760 --> 04:12.360
a colored woman, had her little house, where she spun linen for the townsfolk, making the

04:12.360 --> 04:14.700
loud and notable voice.

04:16.720 --> 04:24.120
At length in the war of 1812 her dwelling was set on fire by English soldiers, prisoners

04:24.120 --> 04:31.180
on parole, when she was away, and her cat and dog and hens were all burned up together.

04:32.300 --> 04:39.420
She led a hard life, and somewhat inhumane. One old frequenter of these woods remembers

04:39.420 --> 04:45.740
that, as he passed her house one noon, he heard her muttering to herself over her gurgling

04:45.740 --> 04:58.640
pot, Ye are all bones, bones! I have seen bricks amid the oak copes there. Down the

04:58.640 --> 05:06.660
road on the right hand, on Brister's Hill, lived Brister Freeman, a handy negro, slave

05:06.660 --> 05:13.360
of Squire Cummings, once. There where grow still the apple trees which Brister planted

05:13.360 --> 05:21.180
and tended, large old trees now, but their fruit still wild and ciderish to my taste.

05:22.780 --> 05:29.440
Not long since I read his epitaph in the old Lincoln Burying Ground, a little on one

05:29.440 --> 05:36.220
side near the unmarked graves of some British grenadiers who fell in the retreat from Concord,

05:37.070 --> 05:46.400
where he is styled Scipio Brister. Scipio Africanus, he had some title to be called,

05:46.900 --> 05:57.820
a man of color, as if he were discolored. It also told me, with staring emphasis, when

05:57.820 --> 06:04.860
he died, which was but an indirect way of informing me that he ever lived. With him

06:04.860 --> 06:13.220
dwelt Fenda, his hospitable wife, who told fortunes, yet pleasantly, large, round, and

06:13.220 --> 06:20.840
black, blacker than any of the children of night. Such a dusky orb as never rose on Concord

06:20.840 --> 06:28.600
before or since. Farther down the hill on the left, on the old road in the woods, are

06:28.600 --> 06:34.260
marks of some homestead of the Stratton family, whose orchard once covered all the slope of

06:34.260 --> 06:41.520
Brister's Hill, but was long since killed out by pitchpines, excepting a few stumps,

06:41.900 --> 06:49.720
whose old roots furnish still the wild stalks of many a thrifty village tree. Nearer yet

06:49.720 --> 06:55.920
to town you come to Breed's location, on the other side of the way, just on the edge of

06:55.920 --> 07:02.340
the wood, ground famous for the pranks of a demon not distinctly named in old mythology,

07:02.820 --> 07:09.280
who has acted a prominent and astounding part in our New England life, and deserves as much

07:09.280 --> 07:16.260
as any mythological character, to have his biography written one day, who first comes

07:16.260 --> 07:24.440
in the guise of a friend or hired man, and then robs and murders the whole family. New

07:24.440 --> 07:25.540
England rum!

07:26.600 --> 07:34.180
But history must not yet tell the tragedies enacted here. Let time intervene in some measure

07:34.180 --> 07:42.680
to assuage and lend an azure tint to them. Here the most indistinct and dubious tradition

07:43.380 --> 07:49.720
says that once a tavern stood, the well the same, which tempered the traveller's beverage

07:49.720 --> 07:57.240
and refreshed his steed. Here then men saluted one another, and heard and told the news,

07:57.620 --> 08:05.020
and went their ways again. Breed's hut was standing only a dozen years ago, though it

08:05.020 --> 08:13.600
had long been unoccupied. It was about the size of mine. It was set on fire by mischievous

08:13.600 --> 08:16.320
boys one election night, if I do not mistake.

08:17.680 --> 08:23.720
I lived on the edge of the village then, and had just lost myself over Davenant's Gondebert,

08:24.440 --> 08:30.620
that winter that I laboured with a lethargy, which, by the way, I never knew whether to

08:30.620 --> 08:37.380
regard as a family complaint, having an uncle who goes to sleep shaving himself, and is

08:37.380 --> 08:43.260
obliged to sprout potatoes in a cellar Sundays in order to keep awake and keep the Sabbath,

08:44.620 --> 08:50.320
or as the consequence of my attempt to read Chalmers' collection of English poetry without

08:50.320 --> 09:00.020
skipping. It fairly overcame my nervi. I had just sunk my head on this when the bells rung

09:00.020 --> 09:06.500
fire, and in hot haste the engines rolled that way, led by a straggling troop of men

09:06.500 --> 09:13.520
and boys, and I among the foremost, for I had leaped the brook. We thought it was far

09:13.520 --> 09:20.500
south over the woods, we who had run to fires before, barn, shop, or dwelling-house, or

09:20.500 --> 09:21.120
all together.

09:22.620 --> 09:24.880
"'It's Baker's Barn,' cried one.

09:25.620 --> 09:31.780
"'It is the Codman place,' affirmed another. And then fresh sparks went up above the wood,

09:31.780 --> 09:34.720
as if the roof fell in, and we all shouted,

09:35.280 --> 09:38.280
"'Concord to the rescue!'

09:38.660 --> 09:44.360
Wagons shot past with furious speed and crushing loads, bearing perchance, among the rest,

09:44.760 --> 09:53.060
the agent of the insurance company, who was bound to go, however far. And ever and anon

09:53.060 --> 09:59.500
the engine bell tinkled behind. More slow and sure and rearmost of all, as it was afterward

09:59.500 --> 10:03.620
whispered, came they who set the fire and gave the alarm.

10:05.360 --> 10:12.920
Thus we kept on like true idealists, rejecting the evidence of our senses, until at a turn

10:12.920 --> 10:18.320
in the road we heard the crackling, and actually felt the heat of the fire from over the wall,

10:19.120 --> 10:27.560
and realized, alas, that we were there. The very nearness of the fire but cooled our ardor,

10:27.960 --> 10:34.360
at first we thought to throw a frog-pond on to it, but concluded to let it burn. It was

10:34.360 --> 10:42.320
so far gone and so worthless. So we stood round our engine, jostled one another, expressed

10:42.320 --> 10:48.140
our sentiments through speaking trumpets, or in lower tone, referred to the great conflagrations

10:48.140 --> 10:54.440
which the world has witnessed, including Bascom's shop, and between ourselves we thought that

10:54.440 --> 11:01.800
were we there in season with our tub, and a full frog-pond by, we could turn that threatened

11:01.800 --> 11:09.520
last and universal one into another flood. We finally retreated without doing any mischief,

11:10.340 --> 11:24.420
returned to sleep and Gondebert, but as for Gondebert I would accept that passage in the

11:24.420 --> 11:28.780
book, and our strangers to wit, as Indians are to powder.

11:30.020 --> 11:35.180
It chanced that I walked that way across the fields the following night, about the same

11:35.180 --> 11:41.000
hour, and hearing a low moaning at this spot, I drew near in the dark and discovered the

11:41.000 --> 11:48.200
only survivor of the family that I know, the heir of both its virtues and its vices, who

11:48.200 --> 11:54.600
alone was interested in this burning. Lying on his stomach and looking over the cellar

11:54.600 --> 12:02.020
wall at the still, smoldering cinders beneath, muttering to himself as is his want, he had

12:02.020 --> 12:08.100
been working far off in the river meadows all day, and had improved the first moments

12:08.100 --> 12:14.680
that he could call his own to visit the home of his fathers and his youth. He gazed into

12:14.680 --> 12:21.340
the cellar from all sides and points of view by turns, always lying down to it, as if there

12:21.340 --> 12:27.820
was some treasure which he remembered concealed between the stones, where there was absolutely

12:27.820 --> 12:34.800
nothing but a heap of bricks and ashes. The house being gone he looked at what there was

12:34.800 --> 12:42.520
left. He was soothed by the sympathy which my mere presence implied, and showed me, as

12:42.520 --> 12:47.400
well as the darkness permitted, where the well was covered up, which, thank heaven,

12:47.480 --> 12:54.120
could never be burned, and he groped long about the wall to find the well sweep which

12:54.120 --> 13:00.020
his father had cut and mounted, feeling for the iron hook or staple by which a burden

13:00.020 --> 13:06.240
had been fastened to the heavy end, all that he could now cling to, to convince me that

13:06.240 --> 13:15.940
it was no common rider. I felt it, and still remark it almost daily in my walks, for by

13:15.940 --> 13:25.000
it hangs the history of a family. Once more on the left, where are seen the well and lilac

13:25.000 --> 13:33.080
bushes by the wall, in the now open field, lived Nutting and La Grosse, but to return

13:33.080 --> 13:40.240
toward Lincoln. Farther in the woods than any of these, where the road approaches nearest

13:40.240 --> 13:47.300
to the pond, Wyman the potter squatted, and furnished his townsmen with earthenware, and

13:47.300 --> 13:54.540
left descendants to succeed him. Neither were they rich in worldly goods, holding the land

13:54.540 --> 14:00.060
by sufferance while they lived, and there often the sheriff came in vain to collect

14:00.060 --> 14:08.340
the taxes, and attached a chip for form's sake, as I have read in his accounts, there

14:08.340 --> 14:14.820
being nothing else that he could lay his hands on. One day in midsummer, when I was hoeing,

14:15.180 --> 14:20.140
a man who was carrying a load of pottery to market stopped his horse against my field

14:20.140 --> 14:26.700
and inquired concerning Wyman the younger. He had long ago bought a potter's wheel of

14:26.700 --> 14:33.480
him and wished to know what had become of him. I had read of the potter's clay and wheel

14:33.480 --> 14:39.500
in scripture, but it had never occurred to me that the pots we use were not such as had

14:39.500 --> 14:46.180
come down unbroken from those days, or grown on trees like gourds somewhere, and I was

14:46.180 --> 14:53.980
pleased to hear that so fictile an art was ever practiced in my neighborhood. The last

14:53.980 --> 15:00.020
inhabitant of these woods before me was an Irishman, Hugh Coyle, if I have spelt his

15:00.020 --> 15:09.460
name with Coyle enough, who occupied Wyman's tenement. Colonel Coyle he was called. Rumors

15:09.460 --> 15:15.700
said that he had been a soldier at Waterloo. If he had lived I should have made him fight

15:15.700 --> 15:23.680
his battles over again. His trade here was that of a ditcher. Napoleon went to St. Helena

15:24.540 --> 15:30.820
Coyle came to Walden Woods. All I know of him is tragic.

15:32.060 --> 15:38.120
He was a man of manners, like one who had seen the world and was capable of more civil

15:38.120 --> 15:44.620
speech than you could well attend to. He wore a great coat in midsummer, being affected

15:44.620 --> 15:52.280
with the trembling delirium, and his face was the color of carmine. He died in the road,

15:52.280 --> 15:58.780
at the foot of Brister's Hill, shortly after I came to the woods, so that I have not remembered

15:58.780 --> 16:07.380
him as a neighbor. Before his house was pulled down, when his comrades avoided it as an unlucky

16:07.380 --> 16:17.200
castle, I visited it. There lay his old clothes, curled up by use as if they were himself,

16:17.630 --> 16:25.760
upon his raised plank bed. His pipe lay broken on the hearth, instead of a bowl broken at

16:25.760 --> 16:33.020
the fountain. The last could never have been the symbol of his death, for he confessed

16:33.020 --> 16:40.400
to me that, though he had heard of Brister's spring, he had never seen it, and soiled cards,

16:41.020 --> 16:49.380
kings of diamonds, spades, and hearts, were scattered over the floor. One black chicken,

16:49.660 --> 16:55.700
which the administrator could not catch, black as night and as silent, not even croaking,

16:56.180 --> 17:04.160
awaited Reynard, still went to roost in the next apartment. In the rear there was the

17:04.160 --> 17:10.880
dim outline of a garden, which had been planted but had never received its first hoeing, owing

17:10.880 --> 17:18.360
to those terrible shaking fits, though it was now harvest time. It was overrun with

17:18.360 --> 17:28.000
Roman wormwood and beggar ticks, which last stuck to my clothes for all fruit. The skin

17:28.000 --> 17:33.100
of a woodchuck was freshly stretched upon the back of the house, a trophy of his last

17:33.100 --> 17:39.440
Waterloo, but no warm cap or mittens would he want more.

17:41.900 --> 17:48.160
Now only a dent in the earth marks the site of these dwellings, with buried cellar stones

17:48.160 --> 17:54.860
and strawberries, raspberries, thimbleberries, hazel bushes, and sumacs growing in the sunny

17:54.860 --> 18:02.840
sward there. Some pitch pine or gnarled oak occupies what was the chimney nook, and a

18:02.840 --> 18:11.180
wheat-scented black birch, perhaps, waves where the door-stone was. Sometimes the well

18:11.180 --> 18:21.800
dent is visible, where once a spring oozed, now dry and tearless grass, or it was covered

18:21.800 --> 18:30.020
deep not to be discovered till some late day, with a flat stone under the sod, when the

18:30.020 --> 18:39.300
last of the race departed. What a sorrowful act must that be, the covering up of wells,

18:40.200 --> 18:51.260
coincident with the opening of wells of tears. These cellar dents, like deserted fox burrows,

18:52.340 --> 19:00.000
old holes, are all that is left, where once were the stir and bustle of human life, and

19:01.240 --> 19:10.960
fate, free will, foreknowledge, absolute, in some form and dialect, or other, were by

19:10.960 --> 19:19.880
turns discussed. But all I can learn of their conclusions amount to just this, that Cato

19:19.880 --> 19:27.040
and Brister pulled wool, which is about as edifying as the history of more famous schools

19:27.040 --> 19:35.180
of philosophy, still grows the vivacious lilac, a generation after the door and lintel

19:35.180 --> 19:43.620
and the sill are gone, unfolding its sweet scented flowers each spring to be plucked

19:43.620 --> 19:51.500
by the musing traveller, planted and tended once by children's hands in front-yard plots,

19:52.360 --> 20:01.940
now standing by wallsides in retired pastures, and giving place to new rising forests, the

20:01.940 --> 20:11.260
last of that sterp sole survivor of that family. Little did the dusky children think that the

20:11.260 --> 20:18.540
puny slip with its two eyes only, which they stuck in the ground in the shadow of the house

20:18.540 --> 20:28.320
and daily watered, would root itself so, and outlive them, and house itself in the rear

20:28.320 --> 20:38.100
that shaded it, and groan man's garden and orchard, and tell their story faintly to the

20:38.100 --> 20:47.160
lone wanderer a half century after they had grown up and died, blossoming as fair and

20:47.160 --> 20:59.060
smelling as sweet as in that first spring. I mark its still tender, civil, cheerful lilac

20:59.060 --> 20:59.620
colours.

21:03.270 --> 21:12.380
But this small village, germ of something more, why did it fail while Concord keeps

21:12.380 --> 21:21.200
its ground? Were there no natural advantages, no water privileges forsooth? Why, the deep

21:21.200 --> 21:28.380
Walden pond and cool brister spring! Privilege to drink long and healthy draughts at these,

21:29.040 --> 21:37.580
all unimproved by these men, but to dilute their glass. They were universally a thirsty

21:37.580 --> 21:47.420
race. Might not the basket, stable broom, mat-making, corn-parching, linen-spinning,

21:47.600 --> 21:55.060
and pottery business have thrived here, making the wilderness to blossom like the rose, and

21:55.060 --> 22:03.380
a numerous posterity have inherited the land of their fathers? The sterile soil would at

22:03.380 --> 22:12.180
least have been proof against a low land degeneracy. Alas, how little does the memory

22:12.180 --> 22:22.160
of these human inhabitants enhance the beauty of the landscape? Again, perhaps, nature will

22:22.160 --> 22:32.440
try, with me for a first settler, and my house raised last spring to be the oldest in the

22:32.440 --> 22:41.940
hamlet. I am not aware that any man has ever built on the spot which I occupy. Deliver

22:41.940 --> 22:48.900
me from a city built on the site of a more ancient city, whose materials are ruins, whose

22:48.900 --> 22:58.780
gardens, cemeteries. The soil is blanched and accursed there, and before that becomes

22:58.780 --> 23:07.560
necessary, the earth itself will be destroyed. With some reminiscences I re-peopled the woods

23:08.440 --> 23:16.460
and lulled myself to sleep. At this season I seldom had a visitor. When the snow lay

23:16.460 --> 23:24.040
deepest no wanderer ventured near my house for a week or fortnight at a time, but there

23:24.040 --> 23:31.260
I lived, as snug as a meadow mouse, or as cattle and poultry which are said to have

23:31.260 --> 23:38.820
survived for a long time buried in drifts even without food, or like that early settler's

23:38.820 --> 23:45.300
family in the town of Sutton, in this state, whose cottage was completely covered by the

23:45.300 --> 23:53.420
great snow of 1717, when he was absent, and an Indian founded only by the hole which the

23:53.420 --> 24:01.700
chimney's breath made in the drift, and so relieved the family. But no friendly Indian

24:01.700 --> 24:09.000
concerned himself about me, nor needed he, for the master of the house was at home.

24:10.200 --> 24:18.800
The great snow, how cheerful it is to hear of, when the farmers could not get to the

24:18.800 --> 24:24.760
woods and swamps with their teams, and were obliged to cut down the shade-trees before

24:24.760 --> 24:31.420
their houses, and when the crust was harder cut off the trees and the swamps, ten feet

24:31.420 --> 24:39.400
from the ground, as it appeared the next spring. In the deepest snows the path which I used

24:39.400 --> 24:45.780
from the highway to my house, about half a mile long, might have been represented by

24:45.780 --> 24:54.240
a meandering dotted line, with wide intervals between the dots. For a week of even weather

24:54.240 --> 25:00.720
I took exactly the same number of steps, and of the same length, coming and going, stepping

25:00.720 --> 25:08.860
deliberately and with the precision of a pair of dividers in my own deep tracks. To such

25:08.860 --> 25:15.500
a routine the winter reduces us, yet often they were filled with heaven's own blue.

25:17.500 --> 25:24.360
But no weather interfered fatally with my walks, or rather my going abroad, for I frequently

25:24.360 --> 25:30.680
tramped eight or ten miles through the deepest snow to keep an appointment with a beech-tree

25:31.140 --> 25:38.840
or a yellow birch, or an old acquaintance among the pines, when the ice and snow causing

25:38.860 --> 25:46.080
their limbs to droop, and so sharpening their tops, had changed the pines into fir-trees.

25:47.600 --> 25:53.840
Wading to the tops of the highest hills when the snow was nearly two feet deep on a level,

25:54.540 --> 26:03.340
and shaking down another snowstorm on my head at every step, or sometimes creeping and floundering

26:03.340 --> 26:11.800
thither on my hands and knees when the hunters had gone into winter quarters, one afternoon

26:11.800 --> 26:21.220
I amused myself by watching a barred owl, Strix nebulosa, sitting on one of the lower

26:21.220 --> 26:29.320
dead limbs of a white pine, close to the trunk, in broad daylight, I standing within a rod

26:29.320 --> 26:36.480
of him. He could hear me when I moved, and crunched the snow with my feet, but could

26:36.480 --> 26:43.520
not plainly see me. When I made most noise he would stretch out his neck and erect his

26:43.520 --> 26:52.380
neck feathers, and open his eyes wide. But their lids soon fell again, and he began to

26:52.380 --> 27:00.380
nod. I, too, felt a slumberous influence after watching him half an hour, as he sat thus

27:00.380 --> 27:10.200
with his eyes half open, like a cat, winged brother of the cat. There was only a narrow

27:10.200 --> 27:18.920
slit left between their lids, by which be preserved a peninsular relation to me, thus

27:18.920 --> 27:26.080
with half-shut eyes looking out from the land of dreams, and endeavoring to realize me,

27:26.700 --> 27:36.400
vague object or moat that interrupts his visions. At length, on some louder noise, or my nearer

27:36.400 --> 27:43.300
approach, he would grow uneasy, and sluggishly turn about on his perch, as if impatient at

27:43.300 --> 27:50.520
having his dreams disturbed. And when he launched himself off, and flapped through

27:50.520 --> 27:59.100
the pines, spreading his wings to unexpected breadth, I could not hear the slightest sound

27:59.100 --> 28:08.340
from them. Thus guided amid the pine boughs, rather by a delicate sense of their neighborhood

28:08.340 --> 28:17.120
than by sight, feeling his twilight way, as it were, with his sensitive pinions, he found

28:17.120 --> 28:23.460
a new perch where he might in peace await the dawning of his day.

28:25.040 --> 28:31.600
As I walked over the long causeway made for the railroad through the meadows, I encountered

28:31.600 --> 28:39.140
many a blustering and nipping wind, for nowhere has it freer play. And when the frost had

28:39.140 --> 28:46.940
smitten me on one cheek, heathen as I was, I turned it to the other also, nor was it

28:46.940 --> 28:53.520
much better by the carriage-road from Brister's Hill, for I came to town still like a friendly

28:53.520 --> 28:59.660
Indian, when the contents of the broad open fields were all piled up between the walls

28:59.660 --> 29:06.380
of the Walden Road, and half an hour sufficed to obliterate the tracks of the last traveler.

29:07.800 --> 29:14.220
And when I returned new drifts would have formed, through which I floundered, where

29:14.220 --> 29:20.300
the busy north-west wind had been depositing the powdery snow round a sharp angle in the

29:20.300 --> 29:28.760
road, and not a rabbit's track, nor even the fine print the small type of a meadow-mouse

29:28.760 --> 29:38.640
was to be seen. Yet I rarely failed to find, even in midwinter, some warm and springy swamp,

29:39.500 --> 29:46.060
where the grass and the skunk cabbage still put forth their perennial verdure, and some

29:46.060 --> 29:50.580
hardier bird occasionally awaited the return of spring.

29:53.800 --> 29:58.700
Sometimes, notwithstanding the snow, when I returned from my walk at evening I crossed

29:58.700 --> 30:06.180
the deep tracks of a wood-chopper leading from my door, and found his pile of whittlings

30:06.180 --> 30:13.560
on the hearth, and my house filled with the odor of his pipe. Or on a Sunday afternoon,

30:13.760 --> 30:21.160
if I chanced to be at home, I heard the crunching of the snow made by the step of a long-headed

30:21.160 --> 30:29.280
farmer, whom from far through the woods sought my house to have a social crack. One of the

30:29.280 --> 30:36.500
few of his vocation who are men of their farms, who donned a frock instead of a professor's

30:36.500 --> 30:43.320
gown, and is as ready to extract the moral out of church or state as to haul a load of

30:43.320 --> 30:51.620
manure from his barnyard, we talked of rude and simple times, when men sat about large

30:51.620 --> 30:59.300
fires in cold bracing weather with clear heads, and when other dessert failed, we tried our

30:59.300 --> 31:06.140
teeth on many a nut which wise squirrels have long since abandoned, for those which have

31:06.140 --> 31:09.600
the thickest shells are commonly empty.

31:11.000 --> 31:18.860
The one who came from farthest to my lodge, through deepest snows and most dismal tempests,

31:19.760 --> 31:30.740
was a poet, a farmer, a hunter, a soldier, a reporter, even a philosopher may be daunted,

31:31.440 --> 31:39.580
but nothing can deter a poet, for he is actuated by pure love. Who can predict that a poet

31:39.600 --> 31:46.040
can predict his comings and goings? His business calls him out at all hours, even when doctors

31:46.040 --> 31:54.280
sleep. We made that small house ring with boisterous mirth, and resound with the murmur

31:54.280 --> 32:04.000
of much sober talk, making amends then to Walden Vale for the long silences. Broadway

32:04.000 --> 32:13.120
was still and deserted in comparison. At suitable intervals there were regular salutes of laughter,

32:13.680 --> 32:20.200
which might have been referred indifferently to the last uttered or the forthcoming jest.

32:21.420 --> 32:28.440
We made many a brand new theory of life over a thin dish of gruel, which combined the advantages

32:28.440 --> 32:36.460
of conviviality with the clear headedness which philosophy requires. I should not forget

32:36.460 --> 32:43.460
that during my last winter at the pond there was another welcome visitor, who at one time

32:43.460 --> 32:49.100
came through the village, through snow and rain and darkness, till he saw my lamp through

32:49.100 --> 32:57.540
the trees, and shared with me some long winter evenings. One of the last of the philosophers

32:58.620 --> 33:06.020
Connecticut gave him to the world. He peddled first her wares, afterwards, as he declares,

33:06.580 --> 33:15.020
his brains. These he peddles still, prompting God and disgracing man, bearing for fruit

33:15.020 --> 33:22.580
his brain only, like the nut its kernel. I think that he must be the man of the most

33:22.580 --> 33:31.160
faith of any alive. His words and attitude always suppose a better state of things than

33:31.160 --> 33:36.960
other men are acquainted with, and he will be the last man to be disappointed as the

33:36.960 --> 33:45.180
ages revolve. He has no venture in the present, but though comparatively disregarded now,

33:45.570 --> 33:53.300
when his day comes laws unsuspected by most will take effect, and masters of families

33:53.300 --> 34:07.120
and rulers will come to him for advice. How blind that cannot see serenity! A true friend

34:07.120 --> 34:15.160
of man, almost the only friend of human progress, an old mortality, say rather, of the most

34:15.180 --> 34:21.680
unwearying, an immortality, with unwearyed patience and faith making plain the image

34:21.680 --> 34:29.840
engraven in men's bodies, the God of whom they are but defaced and leaning monuments.

34:31.040 --> 34:45.160
With his hospitable intellect he embraces children, beggars, insane, and scholars, and

34:45.160 --> 34:53.540
wealth and elegance. I think that he should keep a caravanseri on the world's highway,

34:53.900 --> 35:01.340
where philosophers of all nations might put up, and on his sign should be printed, Entertainment

35:01.340 --> 35:11.720
for man, but not for his beast. Enter ye that have leisure and a quiet mind, who earnestly

35:11.720 --> 35:22.300
seek the right road. He is perhaps the sanest man, and has the fewest crotchets of any I

35:22.300 --> 35:32.460
chance to know, the same yesterday and tomorrow. Of yore we had sauntered and talked, and effectually

35:32.460 --> 35:41.260
put the world behind us, for he was pledged to no institution in it, free born in genus,

35:42.560 --> 35:49.760
which ever way we turned, it seemed that the heavens and the earth had met together, since

35:49.760 --> 35:58.460
he enhanced the beauty of the landscape. A blue-robed man, whose fittest roof is the

35:58.460 --> 36:08.980
overarching sky which reflects his serenity. I do not see how he can ever die. Nature cannot

36:08.980 --> 36:09.940
spare him.

36:11.400 --> 36:18.940
Having each some shingles of thought well dried, we sat and whittled them, trying our

36:18.940 --> 36:26.560
knives and admiring the clear yellowish grain of the pumpkin pine. We waited so gently and

36:26.560 --> 36:34.680
reverently, or we pulled together so smoothly that the fishes of thought were not scared

36:34.680 --> 36:42.340
from the stream, nor feared any angler on the bank, but came and went grandly, like

36:42.340 --> 36:48.700
the clouds which float through the western sky, and the mother-o'-pearl flocks which

36:48.700 --> 36:59.700
sometimes form and dissolve there. There we worked, revising mythology, rounding a fable

36:59.700 --> 37:09.220
here and there, and building castles in the air, for which earth offered no worthy foundation.

37:10.860 --> 37:21.620
Great looker, great expector, to converse with whom was a new England night's entertainment.

37:22.800 --> 37:36.500
Ah, such discourse we had, hermit and philosopher, and the old settler I have spoken of. We three,

37:37.200 --> 37:43.720
it expanded and racked my little house. I should not dare to say how many pounds weight

37:43.720 --> 37:51.600
there was above the atmospheric pressure on every circular inch. It opened its seams so

37:51.620 --> 37:59.000
that they had to be caulked with much dullness thereafter to stop the consequent leak, but

37:59.000 --> 38:09.020
I had enough of that kind of oakum already picked. There was one other with whom I had

38:09.020 --> 38:16.500
solid seasons, long to be remembered, at his house in the village, and who looked in upon

38:16.500 --> 38:24.700
me from time to time, but I had no more for society there. There, too, as everywhere,

38:25.480 --> 38:35.280
I sometimes expected the visitor who never comes. The Vishnu Purana says, The householder

38:35.280 --> 38:43.320
is to remain at Eventide in his courtyard as long as it takes to milk a cow, or longer

38:43.320 --> 38:51.940
if he pleases, to await the arrival of a guest. I often performed this duty of hospitality,

38:52.760 --> 38:59.960
waited long enough to milk a whole herd of cows, but did not see the man approaching

38:59.960 --> 39:01.940
from the town.

